{"id": "16089", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=16089", "title": "July 17", "text": "July 17\n\nBULLET::::- 180 – Twelve inhabitants of Scillium (near Kasserine, modern-day Tunisia) in North Africa are executed for being Christians. This is the earliest record of Christianity in that part of the world.\nBULLET::::- 1048 – Damasus II is elected pope.\nBULLET::::- 1203 – The Fourth Crusade captures Constantinople by assault. The Byzantine emperor Alexios III Angelos flees from his capital into exile.\nBULLET::::- 1402 – Zhu Di, better known by his era name as the Yongle Emperor, assumes the throne over the Ming dynasty of China.\nBULLET::::- 1429 – Hundred Years' War: Charles VII of France is crowned the King of France in the Reims Cathedral after a successful campaign by Joan of Arc.\nBULLET::::- 1453 – Battle of Castillon: The last battle of Hundred Years' War, the French under Jean Bureau defeat the English under the Earl of Shrewsbury, who is killed in the battle in Gascony.\nBULLET::::- 1717 – King George I of Great Britain sails down the River Thames with a barge of 50 musicians, where George Frideric Handel's \"Water Music\" is premiered.\nBULLET::::- 1762 – Catherine II becomes tsar of Russia upon the murder of Peter III of Russia.\nBULLET::::- 1771 – Bloody Falls massacre: Chipewyan chief Matonabbee, traveling as the guide to Samuel Hearne on his Arctic overland journey, massacres a group of unsuspecting Inuit.\nBULLET::::- 1791 – Members of the French National Guard under the command of General Lafayette open fire on a crowd of radical Jacobins at the Champ de Mars, Paris, during the French Revolution, killing scores of people.\nBULLET::::- 1794 – The 16 Carmelite Martyrs of Compiègne are executed ten days prior to the end of the French Revolution's Reign of Terror.\nBULLET::::- 1867 – Harvard School of Dental Medicine is established in Boston, Massachusetts. It is the first dental school in the U.S. that is affiliated with a university.\nBULLET::::- 1821: The Kingdom of Spain cedes the territory of Florida to the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1899 – NEC Corporation is organized as the first Japanese joint venture with foreign capital.\nBULLET::::- 1902 – Willis Carrier creates the first air conditioner in Buffalo, New York.\nBULLET::::- 1917 – King George V issues a Proclamation stating that the male line descendants of the British Royal Family will bear the surname Windsor.\nBULLET::::- 1918 – Tsar Nicholas II of Russia and his immediate family and retainers are executed by Bolshevik Chekists at the Ipatiev House in Yekaterinburg, Russia.\nBULLET::::- 1918 – The , the ship that rescued the 705 survivors from the , is sunk off Ireland by the German ; five lives are lost.\nBULLET::::- 1932 – Altona Bloody Sunday: A riot between the Nazi Party paramilitary forces, the SS and SA, and the German Communist Party ensues.\nBULLET::::- 1936 – Spanish Civil War: An Armed Forces rebellion against the recently elected leftist Popular Front government of Spain starts the civil war.\nBULLET::::- 1938 – Douglas Corrigan takes off from Brooklyn to fly the \"wrong way\" to Ireland and becomes known as \"Wrong Way\" Corrigan.\nBULLET::::- 1944 – Port Chicago disaster: Near the San Francisco Bay, two ships laden with ammunition for the war explode in Port Chicago, California, killing 320.\nBULLET::::- 1944 – World War II: At Sainte-Foy-de-Montgommery. in Normandy Field Marshal Erwin Rommel was strafed by allied aircraft while returning to his headquarters.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – World War II: The main three leaders of the Allied nations, Winston Churchill, Harry S. Truman and Joseph Stalin, meet in the German city of Potsdam to decide the future of a defeated Germany.\nBULLET::::- 1953 – The largest number of United States midshipman casualties in a single event results from an aircraft crash in Florida, killing 44.\nBULLET::::- 1955 – Disneyland is dedicated and opened by Walt Disney in Anaheim, California.\nBULLET::::- 1962 – Nuclear weapons testing: The \"Small Boy\" test shot Little Feller I becomes the last atmospheric test detonation at the Nevada National Security Site.\nBULLET::::- 1968 – Abdul Rahman Arif is overthrown and the Ba'ath Party is installed as the governing power in Iraq with Ahmed Hassan al-Bakr as the new Iraqi President.\nBULLET::::- 1973 – King Mohammed Zahir Shah of Afghanistan, while having surgery in Italy, is deposed by his cousin Mohammed Daoud Khan.\nBULLET::::- 1975 – Apollo–Soyuz Test Project: An American Apollo and a Soviet Soyuz spacecraft dock with each other in orbit marking the first such link-up between spacecraft from the two nations.\nBULLET::::- 1976 – East Timor is annexed, and becomes the 27th province of Indonesia.\nBULLET::::- 1976 – The opening of the Summer Olympics in Montreal is marred by 25 African teams boycotting the games because of New Zealand's participation. Contrary to rulings by other international sports organizations, the IOC had declined to exclude New Zealand because of their participation in South African sporting events during apartheid.\nBULLET::::- 1979 – Nicaraguan dictator General Anastasio Somoza Debayle resigns and flees to Miami, Florida, United States.\nBULLET::::- 1981 – A structural failure leads to the collapse of a walkway at the Hyatt Regency in Kansas City, Missouri, killing 114 people and injuring more than 200.\nBULLET::::- 1984 – The national drinking age in the United States was changed from 18 to 21.\nBULLET::::- 1985 – Founding of the EUREKA Network by former head of states François Mitterrand (France) and Helmut Kohl (Germany).\nBULLET::::- 1989 – First flight of the B-2 Spirit Stealth Bomber.\nBULLET::::- 1989 – Holy See–Poland relations are restored.\nBULLET::::- 1996 – TWA Flight 800: Off the coast of Long Island, New York, a Paris-bound TWA Boeing 747 explodes, killing all 230 on board.\nBULLET::::- 1998 – The 7.0 Papua New Guinea earthquake triggers a tsunami that destroys ten villages in Papua New Guinea, killing up to 2,700 people, and leaving several thousand injured.\nBULLET::::- 1998 – A diplomatic conference adopts the Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court, establishing a permanent international court to prosecute individuals for genocide, crimes against humanity, war crimes, and the crime of aggression.\nBULLET::::- 2000 – During approach to Lok Nayak Jayaprakash Airport, Alliance Air Flight 7412 suddenly crashes into a residential neighborhood in Patna, killing 60 people.\nBULLET::::- 2001 – Concorde is brought back into service nearly a year after the July 2000 crash.\nBULLET::::- 2006 – The 7.7 Pangandaran tsunami earthquake severely affects the Indonesian island of Java, killing 668 people, and leaving more than 9,000 injured.\nBULLET::::- 2007 – TAM Airlines Flight 3054, an Airbus A320, crashes into a warehouse after landing too fast and missing the end of the São Paulo–Congonhas Airport runway, killing 199 people.\nBULLET::::- 2014 – Malaysia Airlines Flight 17, a Boeing 777, crashes near the border of Ukraine and Russia after being shot down. All 298 people on board are killed.\nBULLET::::- 2014 – A French regional train on the Pau-Bayonne line crashes into a high-speed train near the town of Denguin, resulting in at least 25 injuries.\nBULLET::::- 2015 – At least 120 people are killed and 130 injured by a suicide bombing in Diyala Governorate, Iraq.\nBULLET::::- 2018 – 12 new moons are discovered orbiting Jupiter\nBULLET::::- 1476 – Adrian Fortescue, English Roman Catholic martyr (d. 1539)\nBULLET::::- 1487 – Ismail I of Iran (d. 1524)\nBULLET::::- 1499 – Maria Salviati, Italian noblewoman (d. 1543)\nBULLET::::- 1531 – Antoine de Créqui Canaples, Roman Catholic cardinal (d. 1574)\nBULLET::::- 1674 – Isaac Watts, English hymnwriter and theologian (d. 1748)\nBULLET::::- 1695 – Christian Karl Reinhard of Leiningen-Dachsburg-Falkenburg-Heidesheim (d. 1766)\nBULLET::::- 1698 – Pierre Louis Maupertuis, French mathematician and philosopher (d. 1759)\nBULLET::::- 1708 – Frederick Christian, Margrave of Brandenburg-Bayreuth (d. 1769)\nBULLET::::- 1714 – Alexander Gottlieb Baumgarten, German philosopher and academic (d. 1762)\nBULLET::::- 1744 – Elbridge Gerry, American merchant and politician, 5th Vice President of the United States (d. 1814)\nBULLET::::- 1763 – John Jacob Astor, German-American businessman and philanthropist (d. 1848)\nBULLET::::- 1774 – John Wilbur, American minister and theologian (d. 1856)\nBULLET::::- 1797 – Paul Delaroche, French painter and academic (d. 1856)\nBULLET::::- 1823 – Leander Clark, American businessman, judge, and politician (d. 1910)\nBULLET::::- 1831 – Xianfeng Emperor of China (d. 1861)\nBULLET::::- 1837 – Joseph-Alfred Mousseau, Canadian lawyer, judge, and politician, 7th Secretary of State for Canada (d. 1886)\nBULLET::::- 1839 – Ephraim Shay, American engineer, invented the Shay locomotive (d. 1916)\nBULLET::::- 1853 – Alexius Meinong, Ukrainian-Austrian philosopher and academic (d. 1920)\nBULLET::::- 1868 – Henri Nathansen, Danish director and playwright (d. 1944)\nBULLET::::- 1870 – Charles Davidson Dunbar, Scottish soldier and bagpipe player (d. 1939)\nBULLET::::- 1871 – Lyonel Feininger, German-American painter and illustrator (d. 1956)\nBULLET::::- 1879 – Jack Laviolette, Canadian ice hockey player, coach, and manager (d. 1960)\nBULLET::::- 1882 – James Somerville, English admiral and politician, Lord Lieutenant of Somerset (d. 1949)\nBULLET::::- 1888 – Shmuel Yosef Agnon, Ukrainian-Israeli novelist, short story writer and poet, Nobel Prize laureate (d. 1970)\nBULLET::::- 1889 – Erle Stanley Gardner, American lawyer and author (d. 1970)\nBULLET::::- 1894 – Georges Lemaître, Belgian priest, astronomer, and cosmologist (d. 1966)\nBULLET::::- 1896 – Rupert Atkinson, English RAF officer (d. 1919)\nBULLET::::- 1898 – Berenice Abbott, American photographer (d. 1991)\nBULLET::::- 1898 – Osmond Borradaile, Canadian soldier and cinematographer (d. 1999)\nBULLET::::- 1