{"id": "16090", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=16090", "title": "July 18", "text": "July 18\n\nBULLET::::- 477 BC – Battle of the Cremera as part of the Roman–Etruscan Wars. Veii ambushes and defeats the Roman army.\nBULLET::::- 387 BC – Roman-Gaulish Wars: Battle of the Allia: A Roman army is defeated by raiding Gauls, leading to the subsequent sacking of Rome.\nBULLET::::- 362 – Roman–Persian Wars: Emperor Julian arrives at Antioch with a Roman expeditionary force (60,000 men) and stays there for nine months to launch a campaign against the Persian Empire.\nBULLET::::- 452 – Sack of Aquileia: After an earlier defeat on the Catalaunian Plains, Attila lays siege to the metropolis of Aquileia and eventually destroys it.\nBULLET::::- 645 – Chinese forces under general Li Shiji besiege the strategic fortress city of Anshi (Liaoning) during the Goguryeo–Tang War.\nBULLET::::- 1195 – Battle of Alarcos: Almohad forces defeat the Castilian army of Alfonso VIII and force its retreat to Toledo.\nBULLET::::- 1290 – King Edward I of England issues the Edict of Expulsion, banishing all Jews (numbering about 16,000) from England; this was Tisha B'Av on the Hebrew calendar, a day that commemorates many Jewish calamities.\nBULLET::::- 1334 – The bishop of Florence blesses the first foundation stone for the new \"campanile\" (bell tower) of the Florence Cathedral, designed by the artist Giotto di Bondone.\nBULLET::::- 1389 – France and England agree to the Truce of Leulinghem, inaugurating a 13-year peace, the longest period of sustained peace during the Hundred Years' War.\nBULLET::::- 1391 – Tokhtamysh–Timur war: Battle of the Kondurcha River: Timur defeats Tokhtamysh of the Golden Horde in present-day southeast Russia.\nBULLET::::- 1507 – In Brussels, Prince Charles I, is crowned Duke of Burgundy and Count of Flanders, a year after inheriting the title.\nBULLET::::- 1555 – The College of Arms is reincorporated by Royal charter signed by Queen Mary I of England and King Philip II of Spain.\nBULLET::::- 1806 – A gunpowder magazine explosion in Birgu, Malta, kills around 200 people.\nBULLET::::- 1812 – The Treaties of Orebro end both the Anglo-Russian and Anglo-Swedish Wars.\nBULLET::::- 1841 – Coronation of Emperor Pedro II of Brazil.\nBULLET::::- 1857 – Louis Faidherbe, French governor of Senegal, arrives to relieve French forces at Kayes, effectively ending El Hajj Umar Tall's war against the French.\nBULLET::::- 1862 – First ascent of Dent Blanche, one of the highest summits in the Alps.\nBULLET::::- 1863 – American Civil War: Second Battle of Fort Wagner: One of the first formal African American military units, the 54th Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry, supported by several white regiments, attempts an unsuccessful assault on Confederate-held Battery Wagner.\nBULLET::::- 1870 – The First Vatican Council decrees the dogma of papal infallibility.\nBULLET::::- 1872 – The Ballot Act 1872 in the United Kingdom introduced the requirement that parliamentary and local government elections be held by secret ballot.\nBULLET::::- 1914 – The U.S. Congress forms the Aviation Section, U.S. Signal Corps, giving official status to aircraft within the U.S. Army for the first time.\nBULLET::::- 1925 – Adolf Hitler publishes \"Mein Kampf\".\nBULLET::::- 1936 – On the Spanish mainland, a faction of the army supported by fascists, rises up against the Second Spanish Republic in a coup d'etat starting the 3-year-long Civil War, resulting in the longest dictatorship in modern European history.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: During the Beisfjord massacre in Norway, 15 Norwegian paramilitary guards help members of the SS to kill 288 political prisoners from Yugoslavia.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – The Germans test fly the Messerschmitt Me 262 using its jet engines for the first time.\nBULLET::::- 1944 – World War II: Hideki Tōjō resigns as Prime Minister of Japan because of numerous setbacks in the war effort.\nBULLET::::- 1966 – Human spaceflight: Gemini 10 is launched from Cape Kennedy on a 70-hour mission that includes docking with an orbiting Agena target vehicle.\nBULLET::::- 1966 – A racially charged incident in a bar sparks the six-day Hough riots in Cleveland, Ohio; 1,700 Ohio National Guard troops intervene to restore order.\nBULLET::::- 1968 – Intel is founded in Mountain View, California.\nBULLET::::- 1976 – Nadia Comăneci becomes the first person in Olympic Games history to score a perfect 10 in gymnastics at the 1976 Summer Olympics.\nBULLET::::- 1982 – Two hundred sixty-eight Guatemalan \"campesinos\" (\"peasants\" or \"country people\") are slain in the Plan de Sánchez massacre.\nBULLET::::- 1984 – McDonald's massacre in San Ysidro, California: In a fast-food restaurant, James Oliver Huberty opens fire, killing 21 people and injuring 19 others before being shot dead by police.\nBULLET::::- 1992 – A picture of Les Horribles Cernettes was taken, which became the first ever photo posted to the World Wide Web.\nBULLET::::- 1994 – The bombing of the Asociación Mutual Israelita Argentina (Argentine Jewish Community Center) in Buenos Aires kills 85 people (mostly Jewish) and injures 300.\nBULLET::::- 1994 – Rwandan genocide: The Rwandan Patriotic Front takes control of Gisenyi and north western Rwanda, forcing the interim government into Zaire and ending the genocide.\nBULLET::::- 1995 – On the Caribbean island of Montserrat, the Soufrière Hills volcano erupts. Over the course of several years, it devastates the island, destroying the capital, forcing most of the population to flee.\nBULLET::::- 1996 – Storms provoke severe flooding on the Saguenay River, beginning one of Quebec's costliest natural disasters ever.\nBULLET::::- 1996 – Battle of Mullaitivu: The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam capture the Sri Lanka Army's base, killing over 1200 soldiers.\nBULLET::::- 2012 – At least seven people are killed and 32 others are injured after a bomb explodes on an Israeli tour bus at Burgas Airport, Bulgaria.\nBULLET::::- 2013 – The Government of Detroit, with up to $20 billion in debt, files for the largest municipal bankruptcy in U.S. history.\nBULLET::::- 2019 – A man sets fire to an anime studio in Fushimi-ku, Kyoto, Japan, killing at 35 people and injuring dozens of others.\n\nBULLET::::- 1013 – Hermann of Reichenau, German music theorist (d. 1054)\nBULLET::::- 1439 – John V, duke of Saxe-Lauenburg (d. 1507)\nBULLET::::- 1501 – Isabella of Austria, queen of Denmark (d. 1526)\nBULLET::::- 1504 – Heinrich Bullinger, Swiss pastor and reformer (d. 1575)\nBULLET::::- 1534 – Zacharius Ursinus, German theologian (d. 1583)\nBULLET::::- 1552 – Rudolf II, Holy Roman Emperor (d. 1612)\nBULLET::::- 1634 – Johannes Camphuys, Dutch politician, Governor-General of the Dutch East Indies (d. 1695)\nBULLET::::- 1659 – Hyacinthe Rigaud, French painter (d. 1743)\nBULLET::::- 1670 – Giovanni Bononcini, Italian cellist and composer (d. 1747)\nBULLET::::- 1702 – Maria Clementina Sobieska, Polish noble (d. 1735)\nBULLET::::- 1718 – Saverio Bettinelli, Italian poet, playwright, and critic (d. 1808)\nBULLET::::- 1720 – Gilbert White, English ornithologist and ecologist (d. 1793)\nBULLET::::- 1724 – Maria Antonia of Bavaria, Electress of Saxony (d. 1780)\nBULLET::::- 1750 – Frederick Adolf, duke of Östergötland (d. 1803)\nBULLET::::- 1796 – Immanuel Hermann Fichte, German philosopher and academic (d. 1879)\nBULLET::::- 1811 – William Makepeace Thackeray, English author and poet (d. 1863)\nBULLET::::- 1818 – Louis Gerhard De Geer, Swedish lawyer and politician, 1st Prime Minister of Sweden (d. 1896)\nBULLET::::- 1821 – Pauline Viardot, French soprano and composer (d. 1910)\nBULLET::::- 1837 – Vasil Levski, Bulgarian priest and activist (d. 1873)\nBULLET::::- 1843 – Virgil Earp, American marshal (d. 1905)\nBULLET::::- 1845 – Tristan Corbière, French poet (d. 1875)\nBULLET::::- 1848 – W. G. Grace, English cricketer and physician (d. 1915)\nBULLET::::- 1853 – Hendrik Lorentz, Dutch physicist and academic, Nobel Prize laureate (d. 1928)\nBULLET::::- 1861 – Kadambini Ganguly, Indian physician, one of the first Indian women to obtain a degree (d. 1923)\nBULLET::::- 1864 – Philip Snowden, 1st Viscount Snowden, English politician, Chancellor of the Exchequer (d. 1937)\nBULLET::::- 1867 – Margaret Brown, American philanthropist and activist (d. 1932)\nBULLET::::- 1871 – Giacomo Balla, Italian painter (d.1958)\nBULLET::::- 1871 – Sada Yacco, Japanese actress and dancer (d. 1946)\nBULLET::::- 1881 – Larry McLean, Canadian-American baseball player (d. 1921)\nBULLET::::- 1884 – Alberto di Jorio, Italian cardinal (d. 1979)\nBULLET::::- 1886 – Simon Bolivar Buckner Jr., American general (d. 1945)\nBULLET::::- 1887 – Vidkun Quisling, Norwegian military officer and politician, Minister President of Norway (d. 1945)\nBULLET::::- 1889 – Kōichi Kido, Japanese politician, 13th Lord Keeper of the Privy Seal of Japan (d. 1977)\nBULLET::::- 1890 – Frank Forde, Australian educator and politician, 15th Prime Minister of Australia (d. 1983)\nBULLET::::- 1892 – Arthur Friedenreich, Brazilian footballer (d. 1969)\nBULLET::::- 1893 – David Ogilvy, 12th Earl of Airlie, Scottish peer, soldier and courtier (d. 1968)\nBULLET::::- 1895 – Olga Spessivtseva, Russian-American ballerina (d. 1991)\nBULLET::::- 1895 – Machine Gun Kelly, American gangster (d. 1954)\nBULLET::::- 1897 – Ernest Eldridge, English race car driver and engineer (d. 1935)\nBULLET::::- 1898 – John Stuart, Scottish-English actor (d. 1979)\nBULLET::::- 1899 – Ernst Scheller, German soldier and politician, 8th Mayor of Marburg (d. 1942)\nBULLET::::- 1900 – Nathalie Sarraute, French lawyer and author (d. 1999)\nBULLET::::- 1902 – Jessamyn West, American author (d. 1984)\nBULLET::::- 1902 – Chill Wills, American actor (d. 1978)\nBULLET::::- 1905 – Robert Elton Brooker, American business executive (d. 2000)\nBULLET::::- 1906 – S. I. Hayakawa, Canadian-American academic and politician (d. 1992)\nBULLET::::- 1906 – Clifford Odets, A