urh (or Edburga) of Bicester\nBULLET::::- Elizabeth Ferard (Church of England)\nBULLET::::- Frederick of Utrecht\nBULLET::::- Goneri of Brittany\nBULLET::::- Gundenis\nBULLET::::- Marina of Aguas Santas\nBULLET::::- Maternus of Milan\nBULLET::::- Minnborinus of Cologne\nBULLET::::- Pambo\nBULLET::::- Philastrius (or Filaster)\nBULLET::::- Symphorosa\nBULLET::::- Teneu (or Theneva)\nBULLET::::- Theodosia of Constantinople\nBULLET::::- July 18 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)\nBULLET::::- Constitution Day (Uruguay)\nBULLET::::- Nelson Mandela International Day\n\nBULLET::::- BBC: On This Day\nBULLET::::- On This Day in Canada\n"}
{"id": "16091", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=16091", "title": "July 19", "text": "July 19\n\nBULLET::::- AD 64 – The Great Fire of Rome causes widespread devastation and rages on for six days, destroying half of the city.\nBULLET::::- 484 – Leontius, Roman usurper, is crowned Eastern emperor at Tarsus (modern Turkey). He is recognized in Antioch and makes it his capital.\nBULLET::::- 711 – Umayyad conquest of Hispania: Battle of Guadalete: Umayyad forces under Tariq ibn Ziyad defeat the Visigoths led by King Roderic.\nBULLET::::- 939 – Battle of Simancas: King Ramiro II of León defeats the Moorish army under Caliph Abd-al-Rahman III near the city of Simancas.\nBULLET::::- 998 – Arab–Byzantine wars: Battle of Apamea: Fatimids defeat a Byzantine army near Apamea.\nBULLET::::- 1333 – Wars of Scottish Independence: Battle of Halidon Hill: The English win a decisive victory over the Scots.\nBULLET::::- 1544 – Italian War of 1542–46: The first Siege of Boulogne begins.\nBULLET::::- 1545 – The Tudor warship \"Mary Rose\" sinks off Portsmouth; in 1982 the wreck is salvaged in one of the most complex and expensive projects in the history of maritime archaeology.\nBULLET::::- 1553 – Lady Jane Grey is replaced by Mary I of England as Queen of England after only nine days on the throne.\nBULLET::::- 1588 – Anglo-Spanish War: Battle of Gravelines: The Spanish Armada is sighted in the English Channel.\nBULLET::::- 1701 – Representatives of the Iroquois Confederacy sign the Nanfan Treaty, ceding a large territory north of the Ohio River to England.\nBULLET::::- 1702 – Great Northern War: A numerically superior Polish-Saxon army of Augustus II the Strong, operating from an advantageous defensive position, is defeated by a Swedish army half its size under the command of King Charles XII in the Battle of Klissow.\nBULLET::::- 1817 – Unsuccessful in his attempt to conquer the Kingdom of Hawaii for the Russian-American Company, Georg Anton Schäffer is forced to admit defeat and leave Kauai.\nBULLET::::- 1821 – Coronation of George IV of the United Kingdom.\nBULLET::::- 1832 – The British Medical Association is founded as the Provincial Medical and Surgical Association by Sir Charles Hastings at a meeting in the Board Room of the Worcester Infirmary.\nBULLET::::- 1843 – Brunel's steamship the is launched, becoming the first ocean-going craft with an iron hull and screw propeller, becoming the largest vessel afloat in the world.\nBULLET::::- 1845 – Great New York City Fire of 1845: The last great fire to affect Manhattan began early in the morning and was subdued that afternoon. The fire killed four firefighters, 26 civilians, and destroyed 345 buildings.\nBULLET::::- 1848 – Women's rights: A two-day Women's Rights Convention opens in Seneca Falls, New York.\nBULLET::::- 1863 – American Civil War: Morgan's Raid: At Buffington Island in Ohio, Confederate General John Hunt Morgan's raid into the north is mostly thwarted when a large group of his men are captured while trying to escape across the Ohio River.\nBULLET::::- 1864 – Taiping Rebellion: Third Battle of Nanking: The Qing dynasty finally defeats the Taiping Heavenly Kingdom.\nBULLET::::- 1870 – Franco-Prussian War: France declares war on Prussia.\nBULLET::::- 1900 – The first line of the Paris Métro opens for operation.\nBULLET::::- 1903 – Maurice Garin wins the first Tour de France.\nBULLET::::- 1916 – World War I: Battle of Fromelles: British and Australian troops attack German trenches as part of the Battle of the Somme.\nBULLET::::- 1940 – World War II: Battle of Cape Spada: The Royal Navy and the Regia Marina clash; the Italian light cruiser \"Bartolomeo Colleoni\" sinks, with 121 casualties.\nBULLET::::- 1940 – Field Marshal Ceremony: First occasion in World War II, that Hitler appointed field marshals due to military achievements.\nBULLET::::- 1940 – World War II: Army order 112 forms the Intelligence Corps of the British Army.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: The Second Happy Time of Hitler's submarines comes to an end, as the increasingly effective American convoy system compels them to return to the central Atlantic.\nBULLET::::- 1943 – World War II: Rome is heavily bombed by more than 500 Allied aircraft, inflicting thousands of casualties.\nBULLET::::- 1947 – Prime Minister of the shadow Burmese government, Bogyoke Aung San and eight others are assassinated.\nBULLET::::- 1947 – Korean politician Lyuh Woon-hyung is assassinated.\nBULLET::::- 1952 – Opening of the Summer Olympics in Helsinki, Finland.\nBULLET::::- 1961 – Tunisia imposes a blockade on the French naval base at Bizerte; the French would capture the entire town four days later.\nBULLET::::- 1963 – Joe Walker flies a North American X-15 to a record altitude of 106,010 meters (347,800 feet) on X-15 Flight 90. Exceeding an altitude of 100 km, this flight qualifies as a human spaceflight under international convention.\nBULLET::::- 1964 – Vietnam War: At a rally in Saigon, South Vietnamese Prime Minister Nguyễn Khánh calls for expanding the war into North Vietnam.\nBULLET::::- 1969 – Chappaquiddick incident: U.S. Senator Ted Kennedy crashes his car into a tidal pond at Chappaquiddick Island, Massachusetts, killing his passenger Mary Jo Kopechne.\nBULLET::::- 1972 – Dhofar Rebellion: British SAS units help the Omani government against Popular Front for the Liberation of Oman rebels in the Battle of Mirbat.\nBULLET::::- 1976 – Sagarmatha National Park in Nepal is created.\nBULLET::::- 1977 – The world's first Global Positioning System (GPS) signal was transmitted from Navigation Technology Satellite 2 (NTS-2) and received at Rockwell Collins in Cedar Rapids, Iowa, at 12:41 a.m. Eastern time (ET).\nBULLET::::- 1979 – The Sandinista rebels overthrow the government of the Somoza family in Nicaragua.\nBULLET::::- 1979 – The oil tanker \"SS Atlantic Empress\" collides with another oil tanker, causing the largest ever ship-borne oil spill.\nBULLET::::- 1980 – Opening of the Summer Olympics in Moscow.\nBULLET::::- 1981 – In a private meeting with U.S. President Ronald Reagan, French President François Mitterrand reveals the existence of the \"Farewell Dossier\", a collection of documents showing the Soviet Union had been stealing American technological research and development.\nBULLET::::- 1982 – In one of the first militant attacks by Hezbollah, David S. Dodge, president of the American University of Beirut, is kidnapped.\nBULLET::::- 1983 – The first three-dimensional reconstruction of a human head in a CT is published.\nBULLET::::- 1985 – The Val di Stava dam collapses killing 268 people in Val di Stava, Italy.\nBULLET::::- 1989 – United Airlines Flight 232 crashes in Sioux City, Iowa killing 111.\nBULLET::::- 1992 – A car bomb kills Judge Paolo Borsellino and five members of his escort.\nBULLET::::- 1997 – The Troubles: The Provisional Irish Republican Army resumes a ceasefire to end their 25-year paramilitary campaign to end British rule in Northern Ireland.\nBULLET::::- 2014 – Gunmen in Egypt's western desert province of New Valley Governorate attack a military checkpoint, killing at least 21 soldiers. Egypt reportedly declares a state of emergency on its border with Sudan.\n\nBULLET::::- 810 – Muhammad al-Bukhari, Persian scholar (d. 870)\nBULLET::::- 1223 – Baibars, sultan of Egypt (d. 1277)\nBULLET::::- 1420 – William VIII, Marquess of Montferrat (d. 1483)\nBULLET::::- 1569 – Conrad Vorstius, Dutch theologian (d. 1622)\nBULLET::::- 1670 – Richard Leveridge, English singer-songwriter (d. 1758)\nBULLET::::- 1688 – Giuseppe Castiglione, Italian missionary and painter (d. 1766)\nBULLET::::- 1744 – Heinrich Christian Boie, German author and poet (d. 1806)\nBULLET::::- 1759 – Marianna Auenbrugger, Austrian pianist and composer (d. 1782)\nBULLET::::- 1759 – Seraphim of Sarov, Russian monk and saint (d. 1833)\nBULLET::::- 1771 – Thomas Talbot, Irish-Canadian colonel and politician (d. 1853)\nBULLET::::- 1794 – José Justo Corro, Mexican p