 been the recipient of the Eugene V. Debs Award, the John Steinbeck Award and the John Cassavetes Award. He was honored with the Ian McLellan Hunter Award for Lifetime Achievement by the Writers Guild of America (1999).\n\nActors who have regularly worked with Sayles include Maggie Renzi, David Strathairn, Joe Morton, Chris Cooper, Mary McDonnell, Vincent Spano, Kevin Tighe, Josh Mostel, Tom Wright, Gordon Clapp and Angela Bassett.\n\nBULLET::::- \"Night Skies\" – for a more complete history of how the proposed \"Close Encounters of the Third Kind\" sequel became the \"E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial\" story\n\nBULLET::::- Diane Carson and Heidi Kenaga, eds., \"Sayles Talk: New Perspectives on Independent Filmmaker John Sayles\", Wayne State University Press, 2006\nBULLET::::- John Sayles, \"Thinking in Pictures: The Making of the Movie Matewan\", Da Capo Press, 2003\n\nBULLET::::- Senses of Cinema: Great Directors Critical Database\nBULLET::::- Interview April 2007 by Cathy Pryor in the London Independent\nBULLET::::- \"The Rumpus\" interview\nBULLET::::- \"Return of the Independent: Sayles on Sayles\" (5-part interview) from siffblog.com\n"}
{"id": "16112", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=16112", "title": "January 12", "text": "January 12\n\nBULLET::::- 1528 – Gustav I of Sweden is crowned King of Sweden, having already reigned since his election in June 1523.\nBULLET::::- 1554 – Bayinnaung, who would go on to assemble the largest empire in the history of Southeast Asia, is crowned King of Burma.\nBULLET::::- 1616 – The city of Belém, Brazil is founded on the Amazon River delta, by Portuguese captain Francisco Caldeira Castelo Branco.\nBULLET::::- 1808 – John Rennie's scheme to defend St Mary's Church, Reculver, founded in 669, from coastal erosion is abandoned in favour of demolition, despite the church being an exemplar of Anglo-Saxon architecture and sculpture.\nBULLET::::- 1808 – The organizational meeting leading to the creation of the Wernerian Natural History Society, a former Scottish learned society, is held in Edinburgh.\nBULLET::::- 1848 – The Palermo rising takes place in Sicily against the Bourbon Kingdom of the Two Sicilies.\nBULLET::::- 1866 – The Royal Aeronautical Society is formed in London.\nBULLET::::- 1872 – Yohannes IV is crowned Emperor of Ethiopia in Axum, the first imperial coronation in that city in over 200 years.\nBULLET::::- 1895 – The National Trust is founded in the United Kingdom.\nBULLET::::- 1908 – A long-distance radio message is sent from the Eiffel Tower for the first time.\nBULLET::::- 1911 – The University of the Philippines College of Law is formally established; three future Philippine presidents are among the first enrollees.\nBULLET::::- 1915 – The United States House of Representatives rejects a proposal to require states to give women the right to vote.\nBULLET::::- 1916 – Both Oswald Boelcke and Max Immelmann, for achieving eight aerial victories each over Allied aircraft, receive the German Empire's highest military award, the Pour le Mérite as the first German aviators to earn it.\nBULLET::::- 1918 – The Minnie Pit Disaster coal mining accident occurs in Halmer End, Staffordshire, in which 155 men and boys die.\nBULLET::::- 1921 – Acting to restore confidence in baseball after the Black Sox Scandal, Judge Kenesaw Mountain Landis is elected as Major League Baseball's first commissioner.\nBULLET::::- 1932 – Hattie Caraway becomes the first woman elected to the United States Senate.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: United States President Franklin D. Roosevelt creates the National War Labor Board.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – World War II: The Red Army begins the Vistula–Oder Offensive.\nBULLET::::- 1962 – Vietnam War: Operation Chopper, the first American combat mission in the war, takes place.\nBULLET::::- 1964 – Rebels in Zanzibar begin a revolt known as the Zanzibar Revolution and proclaim a republic.\nBULLET::::- 1966 – Lyndon B. Johnson states that the United States should stay in South Vietnam until Communist aggression there is ended.\nBULLET::::- 1967 – Dr. James Bedford becomes the first person to be cryonically preserved with intent of future resuscitation.\nBULLET::::- 1969 – The New York Jets of the American Football League defeat the Baltimore Colts of the National Football League to win Super Bowl III in what is considered to be one of the greatest upsets in sports history.\nBULLET::::- 1970 – Biafra capitulates, ending the Nigerian Civil War.\nBULLET::::- 1971 – The Harrisburg Seven: Rev. Philip Berrigan and five other activists are indicted on charges of conspiring to kidnap Henry Kissinger and of plotting to blow up the heating tunnels of federal buildings in Washington, D.C.\nBULLET::::- 1976 – The United Nations Security Council votes 11–1 to allow the Palestine Liberation Organization to participate in a Security Council debate (without voting rights).\nBULLET::::- 1986 – Space Shuttle program: Congressman Bill Nelson lifts off from Kennedy Space Center aboard \"Columbia\" on mission STS-61-C as a payload specialist.\nBULLET::::- 1990 – A seven-day pogrom breaks out against the Armenian civilian population of Baku, Azerbaijan, during which Armenians were beaten, tortured, murdered, and expelled from the city.\nBULLET::::- 1991 – Persian Gulf War: An act of the U.S. Congress authorizes the use of American military force to drive Iraq out of Kuwait.\nBULLET::::- 1998 – Nineteen European nations agree to forbid human cloning.\nBULLET::::- 2001 – Downtown Disney opens to the public as part of the Disneyland Resort in Anaheim, California.\nBULLET::::- 2004 – The world's largest ocean liner, , makes its maiden voyage.\nBULLET::::- 2005 – Deep Impact launches from Cape Canaveral on a Delta II rocket.\nBULLET::::- 2006 – A stampede during the Stoning of the Devil ritual on the last day at the Hajj in Mina, Saudi Arabia, kills at least 362 Muslim pilgrims.\nBULLET::::- 2010 – An earthquake in Haiti occurs, killing over 100,000 people and destroying much of the capital Port-au-Prince.\nBULLET::::- 2012 – Violent protests occur in Bucharest, Romania, as two-day-old demonstrations continue against President Traian Băsescu's economic austerity measures. Clashes are reported in numerous Romanian cities between protesters and law enforcement officers.\nBULLET::::- 2015 – Government raids kill 143 Boko Haram fighters in Kolofata, Cameroon.\nBULLET::::- 2016 – Ten people are killed and 15 wounded in a bombing near the Blue Mosque in Istanbul.\n\nBULLET::::- 1483 – Henry III of Nassau-Breda (d. 1538)\nBULLET::::- 1562 – Charles Emmanuel I, Duke of Savoy (d. 1630)\nBULLET::::- 1576 – Petrus Scriverius, Dutch historian and scholar (d. 1660)\nBULLET::::- 1577 – Jan Baptist van Helmont, Flemish chemist and physician (d. 1644)\nBULLET::::- 1588 – John Winthrop, English lawyer and politician, 2nd Governor of the Massachusetts Bay Colony (d. 1649)\nBULLET::::- 1591 – Jusepe de Ribera, Spanish painter (d. 1652)\nBULLET::::- 1597 – François Duquesnoy, Flemish sculptor and educator (d. 1643)\nBULLET::::- 1598 – Jijabai Shahaji Bhosale, venerated mother of Indian king Chatrapati Shivaji Maharaj (d. 1674)\nBULLET::::- 1628 – Charles Perrault, French author and academic (d. 1703)\nBULLET::::- 1673 – Rosalba Carriera, Italian painter (d. 1757)\nBULLET::::- 1711 – Gaetano Latilla, Italian composer (d. 1788)\nBULLET::::- 1715 – Jacques Duphly, French organist and composer (d. 1789)\nBULLET::::- 1716 – Antonio de Ulloa, Spanish general and politician, 1st Spanish Governor of Louisiana (d. 1795)\nBULLET::::- 1721 – Duke Ferdinand of Brunswick-Wolfenbüttel, Prussian field marshal (d. 1792)\nBULLET::::- 1723 – Samuel Langdon, American minister, theologian, and academic (d. 1797)\nBULLET::::- 1724 – Frances Brooke, English author and playwright (d. 1789)\nBULLET::::- 1729 – Edmund Burke, Irish philosopher, academic, and politician (d. 1797)\nBULLET::::- 1746 – Johann Heinrich Pestalozzi, Swiss philosopher and educator (d. 1827)\nBULLET::::- 1751 – Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies (d. 1825)\nBULLET::::- 1772 – Mikhail Speransky, Russian academic and politician (d. 1839)\nBULLET::::- 1786 – Sir Robert Inglis, 2nd Baronet, English politician (d. 1855)\nBULLET::::- 1792 – Johan August Arfwedson, Swedish chemist and academic (d. 1841)\nBULLET::::- 1797 – Gideon Brecher, Austrian physician and author (d. 1873)\nBULLET::::- 1799 – Priscilla Susan Bury, British botanist (d. 1872)\nBULLET::::- 1822 – Étienne Lenoir, Belgian engineer, designed the internal combustion engine (d. 1900)\nBULLET::::- 1837 – Adolf Jensen, German pianist and composer (d. 1879)\nBULLET::::- 1849 – Jean Béraud, Russian-French painter and academic (d. 1935)\nBULLET::::- 1853 – Gregorio Ricci-Curbastro, Italian mathematician (d. 1925)\nBULLET::::- 1856 – John Singer Sargent, American painter and academic (d. 1925)\nBULLET::::- 1863 – Swami Vivekananda, Indian monk and philosopher (d. 1902)\nBULLET::::- 1869 – Bhagwan Das, Indian philosopher, academic, and politician (d. 1958)\nBULLET::::- 1873 – Spyridon Louis, Greek runner (d. 1940)\nBULLET::::- 1874 – Laura Adams Armer, American author and photographer (d. 1963)\nBULLET::::- 1876 – Fevzi Çakmak, Turkish field marshal and politician, Prime Minister of the Turkish Provisional Government (d. 1950)\nBULLET::::- 1876 – Jack London, American novelist and journalist (d. 1916)\nBULLET::::- 1876 – Ermanno Wolf-Ferrari, Italian composer and educator (d. 1948)\nBULLET::::- 1877 – Frank J. Corr, American lawyer and politician, 45th Mayor of Chicago (d. 1934)\nBULLET::::- 1878 – Ferenc Molnár, Hungarian-American author and playwright (d. 1952)\nBULLET::::- 1879 – Ray Harroun, American race car driver and engineer (d. 1968)\nBULLET::::- 1879 – Anton Uesson, Estonian engineer and politician, 17th Mayor of Tallinn (d. 1942)\nBULLET::::- 1882 – Milton Sills, American actor and screenwriter (d. 1930)\nBULLET::::- 1884 – Texas Guinan, Canadian-American entertainer and bootlegger (d. 1933)\nBULLET::::- 1889 – Mirza Basheer-ud-Din Mahmood Ahmad, Indian-Pakistani spiritual leader (d. 1965)\nBULLET::::- 1890 – Johannes Vares, Estonian poet, physician, and politician (d. 1946)\nBULLET::::- 1892 – Mikhail Gurevich, Russian engineer and businessman, co-founded the Russian Aircraft Corporation (d. 1976)\nBULLET::::- 1893 – Hermann Göring, German commander, pilot, and politician, Minister President of Prussia (d. 1946)\nBULLET::::- 1893 – Alfred Rosenberg, Estonian-German architect and politician, Reich Minister for the Occupied Eastern Territories (d. 1946)\nBULLET::::- 1894 – Georges Carpentier, French boxer and actor (d. 1975)\nBULLET::::- 1895 – Leo Aryeh Mayer, Polish-Israeli scholar and academic (d. 1959)\nBULLET::::- 1896 – David Wechsler, Romanian-American psychologist and author (d. 1981)\nBULLET::::- 1899 – Pierre Bernac, French opera singer and educator (d. 1979)\nBULLET::::- 1899 – Paul Hermann Müller, Swiss chemist and academic, Nobel Prize laureate (d. 1965)\nBULLET::::- 1901 – Karl Künstler, German SS officer (d. 1945)\nBULLET::::- 1903 – Igor Kurchatov, Russian physicist and academic (d. 1960)\nBULLET::::- 1903 – Andrew J. Transue, American politician and attorney (\"Morissette v. United States\") (d. 1995)\nBULLET::::- 1904 – Mississippi Fred McDowell, American singer-songwriter and guitarist (d. 1972)\nBULLET::::- 1905 – Nihal Atsız, Turkish author, poet, and philosopher (d. 1975)\nBULLET::::- 1905 – James Bennett Griffin, American archaeologist and academic (d. 1997)\nBULLET::::- 1905 – Tex Ritter, American actor and singer (d. 1974)\nBULLET::::- 1906 – Emmanuel Levinas, Lithuanian-French historian, philosopher, and academic (d. 1995)\nBULLET::::- 1907 – Sergei Korolev, Russian colonel and engineer (d. 1966)\nBULLET::::- 1908 – Jean Delannoy, French actor, director, and screenwriter (d. 2008)\nBULLET::::- 1908 – Clement Hurd, American illustrator (d. 1988)\nBULLET::::- 1910 – Patsy Kelly, American actress and comedian (d. 1981)\nBULLET::::- 1910 – Luise Rainer, German-English actress (d. 2014)\nBULLET::::- 1912 – Richard Kuremaa, Estonian footballer (d. 1991)\nBULLET::::- 1914 – Mieko Kamiya, Japanese psychiatrist and psychologist (d. 1979)\nBULLET::::- 1915 – Paul Jarrico, American screenwriter and producer (d. 1997)\nBULLET::::- 1915 – Joseph-Aurèle Plourde, Canadian archbishop and academic (d. 2013)\nBULLET::::- 1916 – Ruth R. Benerito, American chemist and inventor (d. 2013)\nBULLET::::- 1916 – Mary Wilson, Baroness Wilson of Rievaulx, British poet and Spouse of the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom (d. 2018)\nBULLET::::- 1916 – P. W. Botha, South African politician, 8th Prime Minister of South Africa (d. 2006)\nBULLET::::- 1917 – Walter Hendl, American pianist, composer, and conductor (d. 2007)\nBULLET::::- 1917 – Jimmy Skinner, Canadian ice hockey player and coach (d. 2007)\nBULLET::::- 1920 – James Farmer, American activist and politician, co-founded Congress of Racial Equality (d. 1999)\nBULLET::::- 1920 – Jerzy Zubrzycki, Polish-Australian sociologist and academic (d. 2009)\nBULLET::::- 1922 – Tadeusz Żychiewicz, Polish journalist and historian (d. 1994)\nBUL